snippet.textDisplay: They'll enjoy book deals, a film biopic or animated feature, talk shows, etc. There are cultural nuances between the North American mindset and the British, and as challenging as it was for Meghan on the one side of the pond, it might be for Harry on the other given his deeply steeped lineage and loyalty to family (polar opposite of Meghan who dissociated herself from much of hers). All this, against the backdrop of an unstable country in the midst of its identity crisis as it prepares to "divorce" the EU. No matter which side of that political divide, it seems an added salt in the wound off the heels of the Royal Couple's rather recent pomp & fantasy wedding and now abrupt about-face - perhaps the last shimmering filament of British legacy and hope for a Modernised Monarchy the country nee world was excited about. In a past televised interview with William and Kate, he explains the rigours / demands of Kate's role if they marry. He takes her through the steps for months prior to her agreeing, so she truly understands the nature of her position. Perhaps Harry and Meghan would have benefited from this mature approach to the "business" side of love. Or perhaps they did. Or perhaps Meghan admittedly didn't prioritise the warnings from her friends. Or perhaps she had an inkling but chose to ignore it because the love - as well as the long-term plusses - outweighed the rest. But no matter, there are far more urgent issues at stake for the British Monarchy and our deeply dysfunctional global family of orphaned nations all aching for that same sense of comfort, purpose, and inherent worth.
